post_text:
We are excited and humbled by the preliminary, unofficial results of the Gibbon Fairfax Winthrop Schools Operating Levy referendum question. The referendum appears to have passed by a solid majority. We are eternally grateful to our community for this affirmation of our needs. Students in our district will benefit from this investment for years. Thank you for your support.

We recognize that not everyone voted in this election, and not everyone voted Yes. We believe there is common ground in supporting the needs of our children among all of our residents. We look forward to engaging the community through the upcoming strategic planning process, which will inform the school district about its direction into the future.

We look forward to seeing the final unofficial results Thursday night or Friday, once the last few mail in ballots are counted.

Featured Frequently Asked Question: How would the operating levy affect farmers?

Agricultural property will pay taxes for the proposed referendum based only on the value of the house, garage and one acre.

An operating levy is spread on Referendum Market Value.
Agricultural property beyond the dwelling value (home, garage and one acre) and Seasonal Recreational property are exempt from this levy.

post_text:
Featured Frequently Asked Question:

What is the difference between a bond and an operating levy?

An operating referendum is an election asking voters to provide funds that the district uses to run and operate its schools. An operating levy is for running the educational programs at the school and goes to the district‚Äôs general fund.

Bond levies are for funds that the school district uses for new construction, updates to existing facilities, and other additions to school properties. GFW ran a bond referendum in November 2019 for a building project.

The 2020 referendum is entirely for funds dedicated to learning and addressing the district‚Äôs financial situation. Each fund remains separate and cannot be used for another purpose.

Q: How do schools impact the community?

A: According to the National Bureau of Economic Research, there is a definite correlation between school expenditures and home values in any given neighborhood. A report titled, ‚ÄúUsing Market Valuation to Assess Public School Spending,‚Äù found that for every dollar spent on public schools in a community, home values increased $20. These findings indicate that additional school expenditures may benefit everyone in the community, whether or not those residents actually have children in the local public school system.

post_text:
FAQ: What if the school district is dissolved?

A: In the worst case scenario, the district could face dissolution or closure. No single neighboring school district has space for all of our students, so they would be split among many districts. Taxpayers would pay the higher taxes of the neighboring district to which they are assigned, and would still have to pay off GFW's existing debt.

post_text:
Q: How does the tax impact vary for different types of property?

A: Tax rates are set by the state of Minnesota on all types of property, including residential, agricultural, seasonal recreational, and business. An operating levy is spread on Referendum Market Value. Agricultural property beyond the dwelling value (home, garage and one acre) and Seasonal Recreational property are exempt from this levy.

Bond and capital project levies are spread on Net Tax Capacity. All property is subject to tax. Sample tax impacts for the GFW Schools referendum are found here:
https://gfwschools.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/GFW-Tax-Impact-Breakdown.pdf

post_text:
Q: What is the difference between a bond and an operating levy?

A: An operating referendum is an election asking voters to provide funds that the district uses to run and operate its schools. An operating levy is for running the educational programs at the school and goes to the district‚Äôs general fund.

Bond levies are for funds that the school district uses for new construction, updates to existing facilities, and other additions to school properties. GFW ran a bond referendum in November 2019 for a building project. The 2020 referendum is entirely for funds dedicated to learning and addressing the district‚Äôs financial situation. Each fund remains separate and cannot be used for another purpose.

Minnesota Department of Education
May 8 at 9:32 AM ¬∑

Graduation is an important milestone in a student‚Äôs academic journey and deserves to be celebrated. However, to protect the health and safety of our communities this year's celebrations must be different. After consulting with the Minnesota Department of Health, we are advising schools against holding in-person graduation and commencement celebrations. Instead, we encourage schools to find ways to celebrate graduates virtually. We know how much students in the class of 2020 have sacrificed this year, and how disappointing it is not to participate in the milestones or traditions they had imagined. By continuing to take preventative measures, we can keep our loved ones and neighbors safe. Read our full graduation guidance online here: https://education.mn.gov/MDE/dse/health/covid19/.

GFW K-6th grade families: Packet delivery will start today. What does not get delivered today will be delivered on Monday. If possible, please put a box or tote outside your door that we can place the items in. The following grades are receiving items in the deliveries: Pre-K, K, 1st, 3rd and 6th. Teachers of all grades will be in touch with you by Monday at the latest to give you information on Distance Learning. There will also be a post on Facebook and on our GFW website with grade specific information. We know that these are stressful and challenging times for families, and will be in touch with you to make certain you have what you need for your child's distance learning plan. Be assured that we will support you and walk with you through this time.

We have meals available for delivery and pick up. Please contact Beth Walters at beth.walter@gfwschools.org or call 507-207-2201 for more information.

üìå2020.03.13 COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Updateüìå
https://gfwschools.org/district/health-services/coronavirus-covid-19/
*Please click link for more information.

This plan has been developed based on recommendations from MDE, MDH, CDC and a press conference by Governor Walz.

The three key pieces are:

1) The buildings will be used for the educational day, athletic team practices (for now), and community education classes that can run while practicing social distancing (6 foot bubble).
2) No visitor policy in all school buildings.
3) Families are encouraged to start thinking about a backup child-care plan if there is a school closure.

Renville County Sheriff's Office
February 11 at 2:51 PM ¬∑

ATTENTION FAIRFAX, MN AREA RESIDENTS:

There has been a fiber cut in the area, which might affect your ability to call 911. CenturyLink has informed us that about 340 customers in the Fairfax, Gibbon and Lafayette, MN areas are impacted. It is our understanding that repair crews have been dispatched, but we have no estimate on the time until restoration. Also, not all Fairfax residents are included in this outage.

It sounds like cellular service is still intact in the area, so if you have an emergency, please use a cell phone to summon 911.
